Group By
--------
- It is used to create group based on given column/columns.
Syntax
--------
  SELECT columnname from tablename group by columnname;
  SELECT columnname from tablename group by col1, col2;
- It helps to apply aggregate functions like COUNT(), SUM(), AVG(), MAX(), or MIN() on grouped data.

Example#1
---------
Q)Write an SQL query to find the total salary expenditure for each department in the 'employee' table.
- select department,sum(salary) as total from employee2 group by department;
      department |  total
      ---------------------
      HR         |  177000
      IT         |  345000
      Finance    |  225000

Example#2
----------
Q)Write an SQL query to find the number of employees in each department of the 'employee' table
- select department,count(*) as Total_Emp from employee2 group by department;
      department |  Total_Emp
      -----------------------
      HR         |  3
      IT         |  4
      Finance    |  3

Example#3
----------
Q)Write an SQL query to find the maximum salary paid for each designation within each department in the 'employee' table’.
- select department,designation,max(salary) as Total_salary from employee2 group by department,designation;
      department | designation  | Total_salary
      ----------------------------------------
      HR         | Manager      | 75000
      HR         | Associate    | 52000
      IT         | DataEnginner | 85000
      IT         | Tester       | 60000
      Finance    | Analyst      | 70000
      Finance    | Manager      | 90000
      IT         | Manager      | 120000

Example#4 
----------
Q)Write a query to display each department’s minimum, maximum and average salary from employee table.
- SELECT department, max(salary), min(salary), avg(salary) FROM employee2 GROUP BY department;
      department | max(salary) | min(salary) | avg(salary)
      -----------------------------------------------------
      HR         | 75000       | 50000       | 59000.0000
      IT         | 120000      | 60000       | 86250.0000
      Finance    | 90000       | 65000       | 75000.0000

Note
----
- All non group function column specified after select then those all column must be specified after group by 
  clause otherwise we will get error saying not a group by expression.

    SELECT name,department,salary FROM employee GROUP BY department;
    SELECT name,department FROM employee GROUP BY department, name;
- When we are trying to display group function along with another column then we will get error.

    SELECT department, sum(salary) FROM employee; 
    SELECT department, sum(salary) FROM employee GROUP BY department;
- We can use WHERE clause before Group BY

    SELECT designation, sum(salary) FROM employee 
    WHERE department=’IT’
    GROUP BY designation;



